    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "\n*Followup to https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/30889*\n\n### Problem\n\n`vim.ui.img` only supports absolute positioning (overlay).\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`vim.ui.img` should have a convenient way to place an image between lines of text:\n\n```\nline1\n[    ]\n[    ]\nline 2\n```\n\nThis should be possible via extmarks existing features, or if not, we may need to enhance extmarks?\n\nAs part of this work, it probably makes sense to support alignment/padding:\n\n```\nline1\n  [    ]\n  [    ]\nline 2\n```\n\nIf possible,\n- `vim.ui.img` should take some sort of \"region\" parameter that says where the placement is, and it should be driven by a generic mechanism like extmarks or floatwins. \n- `vim.ui.img` should NOT manage its own \"layout\". That is the path to pain and misery.\n\nScrolling:\n\n> Emacs (GUI) has the problem of every image be represented logically as a single line, so a tall image would make scroll jump\n\n### Out of scope\n\nThis particular phase isn't intended to support text \"wrapping around\" or flowing around a block-level div/img.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
